natural problem: Find the angle, in degrees, between the vectors $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}.$
natural solution: If $\theta$ is the angle between the vectors, then \begin{align} \cos \theta &= \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \cdot \left\| \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} \right\|} \\

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes u v :: "real^2"
and angle :: "real^2 \<Rightarrow> real^2 \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "u = vector [2, 5]"
and h1 : "v = vector [-3, 7]"
and h2 : "angle u v = arccos (u \<bullet> v / (norm u * norm v))"
shows  "angle u v = 45"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Find the angle, in degrees, between the vectors $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}.$ The final Answer is 45^\circ
 ### Proof
 If $\theta$ is the angle between the vectors, then \begin{align} \cos \theta &= \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}}{\left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \cdot \left\| \begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} \right\|} \\
 &= \frac{2 \cdot (-3) + 5 \cdot 7}{\sqrt{2^2 + 5^2} \cdot \sqrt{(-3)^2 + 7^2}} \\ &= \frac{29}{\sqrt{29} \sqrt{58}} \\ &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}. \end{align}Therefore, $\cos \theta = \boxed{45^\circ}.$
 *)
